the rehydration of mushrooms can be skipped if you just brown some fresh mushrooms. olive oil substitutes well in place of butter. the recipe can be scaled down to 1 serving if you you use 4 mushrooms, 1 breast half, 4 spoons of brandy, 4 spoons of cream, and pinches of onion powder and dried parsley.

Rating: 4
I've been making this recipe for several months now, and it is a favorite with us. It is on our regular rotation of dishes I make when I don't feel up to something new. The recipe has evolved a bit over time. I really don't like the texture of the dried mushrooms, regardless of how long I soak them, so I use two kinds of fresh instead. I also double the sauce, as we like this dish served over noodles. I will say, the sauce takes quite a while to cook down, so you need to be patient. It does not need artificial thickening, just time. I would suspect that cooks having problems with this sauce "breaking" or failing to thicken may be substituting low or no-fat ingredients for real cream and butter. You really can't make a decent cream sauce with those type of items.

